name: Australian Bass
content: {"content":[{"key":"Species type","type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER"},{"key":"Fish name","type":"text","value":"Australian Bass"},{"key":"Sub header","type":"textarea","value":null},{"key":"Size limit","type":"text","value":"Only 1 over 35 cm in rivers"},{"key":"Bag limit","type":"text","value":"2"},{"key":"About","type":"textarea","value":"Bass are found in fresh and saltwater, in eastern draining rivers from the Mary River in Queensland to the Gippsland Lakes in Victoria."},{"key":"Size","type":"textarea","value":"Maximum of 4kg and 65cm in length."},{"key":"Characteristics","type":"textarea","value":"Bass vary in colour from silver, green and bronze. The fish migrate downstream to the estuaries to breed between around June to August and a fishing closure has been introduced at this time to protect this species. Females are much larger than males. Adult fish are general purpose carnivores. The Bass has a back profile that is arched from above the eyes to the tail with only very slight tapering of the snout. They are a highly sought after sport fish using bait, fly and artificial lure. Although considered excellent eating, the majority of fish are returned to the water unharmed."},{"key":"Confusing species","type":"textarea","value":"Confused with the Estuary Perch (Macquaria colonorum) which has a longer tapered snout with a concave profile."},{"key":"Media","type":"file","value":"https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/fish-smart-images/images/uploads/2016/3/24/Austbass1-1458775570103.jpg"},{"key":"Grouped","type":"checkbox","value":"1"},{"key":"Group type","type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH"},{"key":"Group title","type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit and closed season"},{"key":"Group description","type":"textarea","value":"Australian Bass and Estuary Perch have a combined bag limit of 2 in total, with a possession limit of 4 in total. Closed season in rivers and estuaries May-August inclusive, catch and release fishing permitted during this time."},{"key":"Rule bag limit","type":"text","value":"2 in total - Bag limit combined with Estuary Perch. "},{"key":"Rule legal size","type":"text","value":"Only 1 over 35cm in rivers"},{"key":"Rule possession","type":"text","value":"4 in total - Possession limit combined with Estuary Perch"}]}

name: Australian Salmon
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Australian Salmon","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"5","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Occurs from Tweed Heads through to Port Philip Bay (Victoria) and Tasmania.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Maximum of 6kg and a length of up to 90cm.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Robust body with one continuous dorsal fin (spines & soft rays). Body colour varies from greyish green to steely blue above, usually with yellow to dark spots, and a silver underbelly. name: Flounders and Soles
content:
{"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Flounders and Soles","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"25cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":null,"key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Flounder: Various species inhabit NSW waters including the large-toothed and small-toothed Flounder that are found throughout as well as long-snouted and greenback flounder, found in southern NSW. They are commonly found in bays and estuaries on sandy or silty bottoms.
Sole: Various species inhabit NSW waters including the black sole, found throughout, as well as lemon tongue sole found as far south as Sydney. They are commonly found in bays and estuaries on sandy or silty bottoms.  ","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Flounder:  Range in total length about from 34cm to approx. 55cm.
Sole: These fish range in total length from 27cm to approx. 60cm. ","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Flounder:  Laterally flattened bottom dwellers with both eyes on one side. They have distinct colouration such as spots, irregular blotches and rings on one side of their body with the other being pale.
Sole: These fish are laterally flattened bottom dwellers with both eyes on one side. They have distinct colouration with features such as spots, irregular blotches and lines sometimes present on one side of their body, with the other being pale. They lack a distinct tail and have a smaller mouth than flounder.  ","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Flounder are often misidentified as sole.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/fish-smart-images/images/uploads/2016/3/29/Flounder-1459205575744.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"FLOUNDERN SOLE","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Flounder and Sole have a combined bag limit of 20 in total.","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"20","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"25cm ","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"20","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Estuary Perch
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Estuary Perch","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"Only 1 over 35cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"2","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Estuary Perch lives in coastal rivers and lakes in an area from the Richmond River (NSW) in the north, to the Murray River (South Australia) in the West and as far south as the Arthur and Ansons Rivers (Tasmania).","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Adult fish may attain a total length of about 75cm and a total weight of 10kg.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The body of an Estuary Perch is slightly deeper than that of the Australian Bass, the snout profile is concave and the snout noticeably longer than that of the Australian Bass. The Estuary Perch is a dark grey to silvery on the back becoming paler below. All fins are dark except the outer half of the rear section of the anal fin.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Looks very similar to Australian Bass (Macquaria novemaculeata) which can be distinguished from the Estuary Perch by their straight dorsal head profile.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/3\/29\/Estuaryperch1-1459207017326.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"AUSTRALIAN BASSN ESTUARY PERCH","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit and closed season","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Australian Bass and Estuary Perch have a combined bag limit of 2 in total, with a possession limit of 4 in total. Closed season in rivers and estuaries May-August inclusive, catch and release fishing permitted during this time.","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"2 in total -  Possession limit combined with Estuary Perch","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"Only 1 over 35cm in river","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"4 in total -  Possession limit combined with Estuary Perch","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Hairtail
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Hairtail","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"10","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Large schools are infrequently found in coastal bays and estuaries on Australia's east and west coast. name: Leatherjacket
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Leatherjacket","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"20","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"There are more than 20 species of leatherjackets found throughout NSW waters and, depending on the species, can be caught in estuarine, coastal and offshore waters to depths of 250m or more. In estuarine waters these fish are often found around artificial structures such as pylons and wharfs or are found near seagrass beds e.g. fan-belly, six spine and rough leatherjackets. In coastal and offshore areas they can be found on rocky reefs, sand\/mud bottom or in sponge beds e.g. six spine, yellow-finned, black reef, velvet and chinaman leatherjackets.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Are generally found under 1kg in weight but some offshore species can grow to 3kg.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Several features set leatherjackets apart from other fish species, these include: a small mouth with beak-like teeth, rough sometimes sandpaper like skin, small gill openings, and a single serrated spine on the top of the head that fits neatly into a groove. Most leatherjackets are considered opportunistic feeders and readily feed on many different items including algae, crustaceans, molluscs, fish and polychaete worms.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Could be confused with Triggerfish, however these fish have a dorsal fin rather than a single, serrated dorsal spine.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/3\/29\/Leatherjacket-1459207927304.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"LEATHER JACKETS","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"All leather jacket species have a combined bag limit of 20 in total.","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"20","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"20","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Luderick
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Luderick","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"27cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"10","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Generally restricted to shallow coastal waters and estuaries along the east coast, between southern Queensland (around Noosa Heads) and Tasmania. Luderick are often found in large schools around rocky outcrops and jetties.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Maximum of approximately 4kg and a length of 70cm.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Luderick are generally dark green\/brown in colour with a silvery-grey belly. They possess 8-12 dark, narrow vertical bands across the back. They are mainly herbivorous, feeding on seagrass and green algae, and sometimes molluscs, prawns and polychaete worms. Angling for Luderick has a 'cult-like' following. Long, flexible rods, very small hooks and pencil floats are commonly used, with green weed the preferred bait. Most luderick are caught in winter.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Zebra fish (Girella zebra), however, they are rarely found in southern New South Wales and they possess wide stripes on the body (as wide as the gaps).","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/3\/29\/Luderick2ndVP-1459208078777.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"10","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"27cm","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"20","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Mangrove Jack
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Mangrove Jack","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"5","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Mangrove Jack inhabit coastal waters and rivers from Shark Bay in Western Australia through Torres Straight and Queensland, south to Lake Illawarra in NSW. They are occasionally found in more southern estuaries of NSW.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Reaches a maximum length of approximately 1.2 metres and 16 kg in weight.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The colour of mangrove jack is quite distinctive, varying from bright reddish-brown to dark olive-brown. Fins have a pinkish hue, with the tail generally a darker shade. Each scale has a dark spot, which gives the appearance of cris-crossing lines on the body. Juveniles possess a blue line below the eye, which is also often evident on the adult. The mangrove jack is an extremely strong fighter and regularly finds shelter among submerged snags, making them a very challenging recreational species.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Mangrove jack are often confused with red bass (Lutjanus bohar) on colour alone, however, they lack the deep pit before each eye that is characteristic of the red bass.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/3\/29\/MangroveJackV05-1459208697833.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"5","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"5","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Snapper
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Snapper","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"30cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"10","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Common in coastal and offshore waters from the Capricorn Group in north Queensland around the coast of southern Australia to Coral Bay in Western Australia (including Tasmania).","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Maximum of 20kg and a length of over 1m.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Bright blue spots on body that become less distinct with age, and a background colour of pinkish silver to red. Large fish may have a large bony hump on the head and a fleshy bulge on the snout. Snapper are a popular angling species and are regarded as an excellent table fish. name: Swordfish
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Swordfish","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Swordfish, also known as broadbill swordfish or broadbill, generally inhabit all Australian waters beyond the continental shelf and occur infrequently in the coastal waters of southern Australia. They prefer cooler, temperate waters. Swordfish typically move to surface waters at night and inhabit deeper waters during the day. These vertical movements may be rapid and indicate that the fish can tolerate a broad range of temperatures. Swordfish are generally solitary animals.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Swordfish can reach a maximum length of 4.5 metres and a maximum weight of 540 kg. Male swordfish are rarely seen at sizes exceeding 90kg.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Swordfish are a member of the family Xiphiidae and they are easily recognised by their relatively long and wide flattened sword, which distinguishes them from the marlins and sailfish. They have dorsal fins that are widely separated and they do not possess ventral fins. A large keel is present on each side of the body in front of the tail. Swordfish are a blackish-brown on the upper body and a light brown on the lower body. Adult swordfish inhabiting deep oceanic waters feed on pelagic fish and squid. Those that inhabit shallower continental shelf waters are opportunistic feeders, preying on demersal and pelagic fish. Adult swordfish have no teeth or scales.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"None.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/3\/29\/SwordfishV05-1459211590537.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Whiting
content: {"content":[{"key":"Species type","type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER"},{"key":"Fish name","type":"text","value":"Whiting"},{"key":"Sub header","type":"textarea","value":null},{"key":"Size limit","type":"text","value":"27cm (Sand only)"},{"key":"Bag limit","type":"text","value":"20"},{"key":"About","type":"textarea","value":"Sand whiting, also known as summer whiting, silver whiting and blue-nose whiting, inhabit the inshore waters of eastern Australia including coastal beaches, sand bars, bays, coastal lakes, estuaries and rivers as far as the tidal limits. They typically form large schools across sand banks near river mouths and in the surf zone. Sand whiting generally favour sandy or muddy sand substrates in shallow water to about 6 metres depth."},{"key":"Size","type":"textarea","value":"Sand whiting can reach a maximum length of around 47 centimetres."},{"key":"Characteristics","type":"textarea","value":"Sand whiting are a member of the family Sillaginidae. They are silvery white in colour, with plain yellowish sides. Dark blotches are present at the base of the pectoral fins. In terms of shape, they are fairly elongate and only slightly compressed. The snout is relatively long and conical. Sand whiting feed on marine invertebrates, including crustaceans (yabbies, prawns and soldier crabs), polychaete worms and bivalve molluscs (pipis). Sand whiting use their conical snout to forage for benthic animals through sand and mud. This species is known to bury itself in soft sand and mud when alarmed."},{"key":"Confusing species","type":"textarea","value":"Sand whiting are similar in appearance to yellow-finned whiting (Sillago schomburgkii), however the dark blotches on the pectoral fin base in sand whiting are absent in yellow-finned whiting."},{"key":"Media","type":"file","value":"https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/fish-smart-images/images/uploads/2016/3/29/whitingV05-1459223286289.jpg"},{"key":"Grouped","type":"checkbox","value":"1"},{"key":"Group type","type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"WHITING"},{"key":"Group title","type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit"},{"key":"Group description","type":"textarea","value":"Whiting  have a combined bag limit of 20 in total."},{"key":"Rule bag limit","type":"text","value":"20 in total"},{"key":"Rule legal size","type":"text","value":"27 cm (Sand whiting only)"},{"key":"Rule possession","type":"text","value":"20 in total"}]}

name: Pearl Perch
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Pearl Perch","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"30cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"5","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Pearl perch are found in small schools on deeper offshore reefs, between Port Macquarie in NSW and Rockhampton in Queensland.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Maximum weight of around 5.5kg and 70cm in length.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"They are pearlish-green-silver-grey in colour with golden-brown specks on the scales. name: Rock Blackfish (Black Drummer)
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Rock Blackfish (Black Drummer)","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"30cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"10","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Eastern rock blackfish are found in surge areas of rocky shorelines along the NSW coast, as well as southern Queensland, Victoria and north-eastern Tasmania.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Maximum weight of approximately 9kg and a length of 76cm.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Rock blackfish have a blackish-brown to grey body. They possess a dorsal fin (with 13 spines) that extends to the tail base. Their diet includes cunjevoi, red bait crab and cabbage seaweed. They are a tough fighter and a great sportfish, using their strong swimming tail to hide under rock ledges or in crevices.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Silver Drummer (Kyphosus sydneyanus) are found on coastal reefs in NSW, South Australia and southern Western Australia. name: Bream
content: {"content":[{"key":"Species type","type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER"},{"key":"Fish name","type":"text","value":"Bream"},{"key":"Sub header","type":"textarea","value":null},{"key":"Size limit","type":"text","value":"25cm"},{"key":"Bag limit","type":"text","value":null},{"key":"About","type":"textarea","value":"Yellowfin bream: Found along the NSW coast, as well as in Queensland and Victoria. Bream inhabit estuaries up to the brackish water limit (the change from salt to freshwater) and inshore rocky reef habitats near ocean beaches and rocky headlands. Black Bream:  Commonly referred to as the blue-nose bream or southern bream and is found in brackish and fresh waters of estuaries and rivers (occasionally found in coastal waters of southern and western Australia in times of flood). The Black Bream's range extends from southern NSW, Victoria, South Australia and into Western Australia as far north as Shark Bay."},{"key":"Size","type":"textarea","value":"Yellowfin Bream: Maximum weight of 4kg and a length of 60 cm.\\r\\nBlack Bream: The black bream is known to grow to a maximum length of 54cm (approx. 3.6kg)."},{"key":"Characteristics","type":"textarea","value":"Yellowfin bream: Silver to olive-green body with yellowish pectoral, ventral and anal fins. They are opportunistic feeders with their diet including small crabs, prawns, molluscs, pipis and small fish. Black Bream:  The upper body of the black bream is typically a silvery-olive brown colour or bronzy-black, even greenish at times, depending on habitat. The ventral and anal fins are brownish-black in colour, with a small black spot at the base of the pectoral fin."},{"key":"Confusing species","type":"textarea","value":"Tarwhine have rounded, convex heads and a gold spot on each scale giving the fish a series of longitudinal bands."},{"key":"Media","type":"file","value":"https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/fish-smart-images/images/uploads/2016/3/31/Yellowfinbream1psd-1459379283108.jpg"},{"key":"Grouped","type":"checkbox","value":"1"},{"key":"Group type","type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"BREAM AND TARWHINE"},{"key":"Group title","type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit"},{"key":"Group description","type":"textarea","value":"Bream and Tarwhine have a combined bag limit of 10 in total, with a possession limit of 20."},{"key":"Rule bag limit","type":"text","value":"10"},{"key":"Rule legal size","type":"text","value":"25 cm"},{"key":"Rule possession","type":"text","value":"10"}]}

name: Flathead, All other (including Bluespotted and Tiger)
content:
{"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Flathead, All other (including Bluespotted and Tiger)","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"33cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":null,"key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Tiger flathead:  Found from the NSW north coast south through to Portland in Victoria, including Bass Straight and Tasmania. This species is predominantly found offshore but tiger flathead also inhabit shallow coastal bays. Tiger flathead are more common south of Nowra.
Bluespotted flathead:  (Northern): The Northern Flathead (P. arenarius), sometimes known as the flag-tailed flathead, is endemic to Australian waters and is commonly found along beaches and in estuaries of Northern NSW. Its range extends through Queensland into the Northern Territory and as far south as Carnarvon in Western Australia. It has been recorded as far south as Jervis Bay on the east coast.
Bluespotted flathead (Southern):  The Southern Flathead (P. arenarius), sometimes known as the slimy flathead or bay flathead, is also endemic to Australian waters. It is common along the beaches and estuaries of southern Australia. Its range extends from Red Rock in Northern NSW through Victoria, Tasmania and South Australia into Western Australia, as far north as Lancelin (most abundant in Victoria and Tasmania). Found in shallow coastal bays to the tidal limits of estuaries and to a depth of up to 100 metres.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Tiger flathead: Maximum of 3kg and 65cm in length.
Bluespotted flathead (Northern): One of the smaller species of flathead, growing to a maximum length of 45cm (approx. 0.7kg).
Bluespotted flathead (Southern):  Grows to a maximum length of 55cm (approx. 1.3kg).","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Tiger flathead: Bright orange/brown spots on the head and body, with red/brown spots on upper half of the tail. They have large teeth on the roof of their mouth and a sharp spine on each side of the head. Considered good eating.
Bluespotted flathead (Northern): The Northern Flathead has a pale brown body speckled with pinkish-red spots. The caudal fin (tail) is the best way to identify the northern sand flathead, with a pattern of almost horizontal flag-like black stripes across the tail (three distinct black bars on the upper portion and two on the lower portion of the caudal fin). Unlike many other flathead species, the northern sand flathead sporadically appears in schools.
Bluespotted flathead (Southern): The Southern Flathead has a brownish-grey body speckled with reddish-brown spots. Similar to other flathead species, the caudal fin (tail) is the best way to identify the Southern Flathead. It is recognisable by a large brownish-black blotch on the lower edge, with smaller reddish-brown spots on the upper portion of the caudal fin.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Tiger flathead: The reddish/orange spots on the head and body separate this from other flathead.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/fish-smart-images/images/uploads/2016/3/31/easterBluespottedFlathead(SandFlathead)-1459385593037.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"FLATHEAD","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"There is a combined bag limit for Bluespotted and Tiger Flathead of 10 in total and a combined possession limit of 20","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"10","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"33 cm","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"20","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Mackerel, Spanish (Narrow-barred)
content: {"content":[{"key":"Species type","type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER"},{"key":"Fish name","type":"text","value":"Mackerel, Spanish (Narrow-barred)"},{"key":"Sub header","type":"textarea","value":"Mackerel"},{"key":"Size limit","type":"text","value":"75cm"},{"key":"Bag limit","type":"text","value":null},{"key":"About","type":"textarea","value":"Narrow-barred Spanish mackerel, known internationally as Tanguigue, inhabit coastal waters from Perth, Western Australia, around the Top End to Bermagui in NSW. Spanish mackerel have also been caught in Victorian and Tasmanian waters. Spanish Mackerel are known for potentially carrying Ciguatera toxin. Ciguatera toxin does not affect the appearance, odour or taste of fish. Processes like cooking or freezing will not destroy it and there is no method for removing it from fish. To minimise the risk, consumers should avoid eating large Spanish Mackerel (10kgs or more, in accordance with NSW industry experts) and avoid eating the\r\nhead, roe, liver and viscera, as the toxin is concentrated in these areas. Ciguatera is more common in warmer northern waters of Queensland and the Northern Territory."},{"key":"Size","type":"textarea","value":"This is the largest of the Australian mackerels, reaching a maximum length of approximately 2.4 metres and 70 kg in weight."},{"key":"Characteristics","type":"textarea","value":"The upper body varies from bright blue to dark grey in colour that fades to a silvery-blue over the sides. More than 40 narrow grey-blue wavy, vertical bars are present on each side of the fish. The large dip in the lateral line below the second dorsal fin is a clear diagnostic feature of the narrow-barred mackerel."},{"key":"Confusing species","type":"textarea","value":"Similar in appearance to wahoo. Narrow-barred mackerel have less dorsal fin spines (15-18 compared with 23-27), the second dorsal fin is located closer to the centre of the body and they have a more prominent fork in their tail."},{"key":"Media","type":"file","value":"https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/fish-smart-images/images/uploads/2016/3/31/SpanishmackerelV05-1459387597038.jpg"},{"key":"Grouped","type":"checkbox","value":"1"},{"key":"Group type","type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL"},{"key":"Group title","type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit"},{"key":"Group description","type":"textarea","value":"Spanish and Spotted Mackerel have a combined bag limit of 5 in total"},{"key":"Rule bag limit","type":"text","value":"5. name: Marlin, Striped
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Marlin, Striped","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Striped marlin inhabit tropical to temperate waters and can be found in ocean waters off all Australian states including Tasmania, but are more numerous in eastern Australia. They are a true oceanic species that prefer to inhabit cooler water than either the blue marlin (Makaira mazara) or black marlin (Makaira indica).","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Striped marlin can reach a length of 4.2 metres and can weigh up to 200kg.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Striped marlin are a member of the family Istiophoridae. The body of striped marlin is more compressed compared to the more rounded body section of other marlin. The high pointed dorsal fin equals or exceeds the depth of the body and the pectoral fin can be folded flush against the body. Striped marlin have a longer lower jaw than other marlin species and display 12 to 16 light blue vertical bars along the body, which may remain after death. It is purple-blue in colour on the top of the body and silvery-white on the sides. This species is carnivorous and non-selective in its feeding habits. The diet of striped marlin is comprised mainly of surface fish such as squid, lancetfish, anchovy, pilchard, trevally, small tuna-like species and flutemouths.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Striped marlin have a clearly visible lateral line, which distinguishes them from blue marlin where the lateral line is almost invisible. Striped marlin also has a more compressed body structure and a longer lower jaw than that seen in either blue or black marlin.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/3\/31\/StripedMarlin2-1459392237264.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"Rule possession"}]}

They are common in NSW waters, occurring in shallow coastal waters to a depth of approximately 30 metres.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Maximum of approximately 4kg and 65cm in length.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The upper body varies from red to pale brown in colour. name: Mullet (Juvenile/Poddy)
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Mullet (Juvenile\/Poddy)","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Mullet","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"<15cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":null,"key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The term \"poddy\" refers to the juvenile of a particular species. Poddy mullet are very popular with anglers for use as live bait, especially in estuaries and around river mouths for flathead and off the beach when targeting tailor and mulloway\/jewfish. However, it is difficult to identify the various species of mullet, particularly when they are juveniles. As a result anglers may take any species of mullet, for use as live bait only, provided they are less than 15cm and the total number does not exceed 20.\r\nParticularly abundant in estuaries and coastal waters of NSW, the latter two species are more prevalent in southern NSW.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Sea (bully) mullet reach a maximum length of approximately 75 centimetres and 8kg in weight, while flat-tail mullet and sand mullet are a smaller species, reaching a maximum length of approximately 45cm.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The head of the sea (bully) mullet is very broad when viewed from above, but narrowed when viewed from the side. The back of these mullet may vary in colour from steely blue, olive green to brown, while the belly is a bright silvery white colour and the body is fat and cylindrical. The sand mullet is a much more streamlined fish with a more pointed, narrower head and smaller eyes. A small, dark blotch is evident at the base of its pectoral fins and the fish is much more silver overall.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"None","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/3\/31\/MulletV05-1459398641442.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"MULLET JUVENILE","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Size limit for live bait only","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Sea (Bully) Mullet under 15cm may be used for live bait only.","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"20 in total for live bait only","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"Under 15 cm for live bait only","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"20 in total for live bait only","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Marlin, Black
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Marlin, Black","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Black marlin are found in tropical and subtropical waters of the Indian and Pacific Oceans. Occasionally found in waters off Australia's southern areas during the summer months. Black marlin are a highly mobile, pelagic fish that inhabit almost any depth in the ocean, but usually prefer areas offshore.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Black marlin can grow to a maximum length of 5 metres and can weigh over 700 kilograms. Males are smaller than females.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Black marlin are a member of the family Istiophoridae. They possess a long, pointed bill, a retractable dorsal fin and a rigid pectoral fin, which cannot be pressed against the side of the body. Black marlin have two keels on either side of the tail base. Their name is derived from the colouration they take on when dead. Unlike blue (Makaira mazara) and striped marlin (Tetrapturus audax), black marlin do not usually have any blotches or stripes along the body. Juvenile black marlin feed on tropical pilchards and herring while adults feed on trevally, tuna-like fishes and scad. ","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Black marlin are sometimes confused with blue marlin, however black marlin have comparatively low and rounded dorsal and anal fins. The pectoral fins of blue marlin can be folded against the body.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/1\/BlackMarlin2002copy-1459468442566.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Marlin, Blue
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Marlin, Blue","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Blue marlin are pelagic fish, but rarely found in ocean waters less than 100 metres deep. Compared to other marlins, blue marlin have the most tropical distribution. They can be found throughout eastern and western Australian waters and depending on warm ocean currents, as far south as Tasmania.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Blue marlin can reach a maximum length of 5 metres. Females can weigh more than 900kg, while males only reach a weight of around 170 kilograms.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Blue marlin are a member of the family Istiophoridae. They possess a long, pointed bill and a non-rigid pectoral fin that can be folded against the body. The back of the fish is cobalt-blue in colour, breaking into silvery white on the lower half of the body. About 15 pale blue bars can be seen along the body, which fade after death. They feed on squid and finfish, particularly tuna-like species.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Blue marlin are distinguished from black marlin (Makaira indica) by the non-rigid pectoral fin and the presence of blue bars displayed along the body. The lower dorsal fin height of blue marlin distinguishes it from striped marlin (Tetrapturus audax), whose dorsal fin height is equal to its body depth.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/1\/BlueMarlin-1459469640015.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Tuna, Albacore
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Tuna, Albacore","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"90 cm or above - 2 in total,  Less than 90 cm - 5 in total","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"90 cm or above - 2 in total,  Less than 90 cm - 5 in total","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Albacore, also called albacore tuna or longfin tuna, are pelagic fish that are present in east and south Australian waters and from east of Torres Strait to the north west shelf. The distribution of albacore is related to oxygen concentration and water temperature. Whilst albacore feed at the surface, they primarily live at the thermocline, which is the boundary separating warmer surface waters and deeper, cooler waters. Mature albacore travel from temperate waters to the tropics but return to temperate waters after spawning.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Albacore can reach a maximum length of 1.5 metres and can weigh more than 40kg. Anglers commonly catch fish between 50 and 90 cm and a weight of 3 - 22kg.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Albacore are a member of the family Scombridae and are recognised by their very long pectoral fins, which are the longest of all tunas. Albacore are also characterised by a dark yellow first dorsal fin and pale yellow second dorsal fin. Albacore are opportunistic carnivores that feed on planktonic crustaceans, squid and small fish.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Similar to yellowfin tuna, however, albacore possess an elongated pectoral fin and a distinctive white rear border on the caudal fin, which is unique to this species.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/1\/AlbacoreV05-1459470045065.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"TUNA","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Combined group bag limit of 2 in total 90cm or above, if less than 90cm then  5 in total. name: Tuna, Bigeye
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Tuna, Bigeye","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"90 cm or above - 2 in total,  Less than 90 cm - 5 in total","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"90 cm or above - 2 in total,  Less than 90 cm - 5 in total","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Bigeye tuna (or bigeye) are oceanic fish present throughout Australian waters. Geographic distribution is limited by temperature and oxygen concentrations. They have a greater tolerance to lower temperature and oxygen levels than other tunas, therefore, they tend to occupy deeper waters. Females give birth to live young that are approximately 65 cm long. Adults can grow to 6 m in length however they are only rarely observed over 4.5 m.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Great Hammerhead is one of 9 species of hammerhead that occur globally. Of these, only 3 species occur in NSW waters \u2013 Great Hammerhead, Scalloped Hammerhead and Smooth Hammerhead. Similar to all members of the hammerhead family, the Great Hammerhead Shark has a large flattened 'hammer like' head with wide set eyes. The Great Hammerhead Shark can be distinguished by their large size; very tall and distinctly sickle shaped first dorsal fin; large second dorsal fin; relatively straight frontal margin of their hammer-shaped head; strongly concave rear edge of their pelvic fins; and their clearly serrated teeth. Great Hammerheads have a wide thick head with eyes at the margins of the hammer which is almost rectangular in shape. The species also has a tapered body which is bronze-pale brown on the dorsal surfaces and pale on the ventral surfaces.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Great Hammerhead Shark is often confused with other species of hammerhead including the Smooth Hammerhead and the Scalloped Hammerhead Shark. The Smooth Hammerhead is the most common species of hammerhead in NSW waters and can be distinguished from the Great Hammerhead by the curved front margin of their head; dusky colouring beneath the tips of their pectoral fins, smaller but relatively erect dorsal first fin; and their smooth or only weakly serrated teeth.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/5\/GreatHammerhead15.08.12-1459818559766.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Shark, Grey Nurse
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Shark, Grey Nurse","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Threatened Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Australian east coast population of Grey nurse Sharks aggregate at, and migrate between a number of key sites along the coast of NSW and southern Queensland from Montague Island in the south to Fraser Island in the north.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Grey nurse Sharks can grow to a maximum length of 3.2m.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Grey nurse Sharks have large, stout bodies tapered at each end, a pointed snout and small eyes. The upper surface of Grey nurse Sharks is bronze coloured, and the underside is pale white. Juveniles often have dark spots on the lower half of the body and the caudal (tail) fin. These spots fade as the shark becomes larger, but sometimes persist on adults. They have two distinctive large dorsal (top) fins of similar size. The first dorsal fin is set well back from the pectoral (side) fins. The anal fin is similar in size to both dorsal fins. name: Shark, Scalloped Hammerhead
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Shark, Scalloped Hammerhead","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Threatened Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Scalloped Hammerhead Shark has a circumglobal distribution in tropical and warm temperate seas between 45?N to 34?S, but occurs more frequently at higher latitudes during the warmer months. Scalloped Hammerheads may be found throughout the seas around northern Australia as far south as Sydney, NSW (34?S) and Geographe Bay WA (33?S).","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Scalloped Hammerhead Shark typically grows to approximately 3.5 metres in length, although there are unconfirmed reports of larger individuals. They are a timid shark and not considered dangerous to humans.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Scalloped Hammerhead is on of 9 species of hammerhead that occur globally. Of these, only 3 species occur in NSW waters \u2013 Scalloped Hammerhead, Great Hammerhead and Smooth Hammerhead. The Scalloped Hammerhead Shark can be distinguished by their large flattened 'hammer-like' head, with wide set eyes and prominent central scallop-like indentation in the front margin of the head. The Scalloped Hammerhead Shark has a tapered shape, with light brown, bronze or olive colouring on the dorsal surfaces, fading to white below. The underside of the pectoral fin tips has a dusky colouration.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Scalloped Hammerhead Shark is often confused with other species of hammerhead sharks, including the Smooth Hammerhead and the Great Hammerhead shark. On Scalloped Hammerheads the narial groove that occurs on the under-surface of the frontal margin of the head is shorter and less developed, while the central scallop is usually more prominent and well developed than on the Smooth Hammerhead. The teeth of the Scalloped Hammerhead are also usually smooth edged, while the Smooth Hammerhead usually has weakly serrated teeth.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2018\/8\/3\/Scalloped-hammerhead-1533274679324.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Murray Cod
content: {"content":[{"key":"Species type","type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER"},{"key":"Fish name","type":"text","value":"Murray Cod"},{"key":"Sub header","type":"textarea","value":null},{"key":"Size limit","type":"text","value":"55-75cm"},{"key":"Bag limit","type":"text","value":"2"},{"key":"About","type":"textarea","value":"Murray Cod, also referred to as Cod or Codfish, were once abundant throughout the Murray-Darling river system, but overfishing and environmental changes have drastically reduced its numbers. The species has been selectively stocked in other river systems in New South Wales, Victoria and Western Australia, but has generally failed to establish itself in those areas. Murray cod generally prefer slow flowing, turbid water in streams and rivers, favouring deeper water around boulders, undercut banks, overhanging vegetation and logs. Small numbers are still present in the Nepean River (NSW) and Yarra River (VIC)."},{"key":"Size","type":"textarea","value":"Murray Cod reach a maximum size of about 1.8 metres and 113kg."},{"key":"Characteristics","type":"textarea","value":"Murray Cod are a member of the family Percichthyidae and have a relatively large, elongate and deep body. They have small eyes and a short snout, which has a distinct concave profile. The mouth is large with a protruding lower jaw. Murray Cod possess a cream to olive green colour with dark grey to greenish blotches over the head and body. The ventral surface (belly) is generally white in colour. These cod are voracious feeders and predators. Their diet consists of fish, crustaceans, water birds, frogs, turtles and terrestrial animals such as mice and snakes."},{"key":"Confusing species","type":"textarea","value":"Similar to the Mary River Cod, Eastern Cod and Trout Cod."},{"key":"Media","type":"file","value":"https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/fish-smart-images/images/uploads/2016/5/3/MurraycodVP-1462234792937.jpg"},{"key":"Grouped","type":"checkbox","value":"1"},{"key":"Group type","type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"MURRAY COD"},{"key":"Group title","type":"text","value":"Slot limit and closed season"},{"key":"Group description","type":"textarea","value":"Murray Cod have a slot limit of 55-75cm in place. name: Crayfish, Murray
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Crayfish, Murray","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Threatened Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"10 -12 cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"2","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Murray crayfish can be found in the Murray River upstream of Mildura, in the Murrumbidgee River and in some dams, and are the only species in the Euastacus genus that live in both cold and warm water habitats. Scientific name: Euastacus armatus.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Murray crayfish have been reported to grow to 3 kg and are the second largest freshwater crayfish in the world behind the Tasmanian freshwater crayfish.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Murray crayfish are slow-growing animals and may take up to 9 years until they reach their legal length of 10cm. They are opportunistic feeders, feeding on decaying animals and plants. Like all other freshwater crayfish species, they undertake a series of moults as they grow. Murray crayfish become more active during the winter months. Mating activity usually occurs during May, most likely cued to a decline in water temperatures. Females carry eggs under their tails (attached to the mother\u2019s pleopods). Eggs hatch during late spring, around 140 days after fertilisation. Juveniles remain attached to the mothers pleopods until they have gone through a series of moults, after which time they become self sufficient.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/13\/MurraycrayVP-1460511621447.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"MURRAY CRAYFISH","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Restricted area, closed season and slot limit","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The following waters are open to fishing for Murray crayfish from 1 June to 31 August (including all tributaries, lakes, lagoons, dams, reservoirs, ponds, canals, channels or waterways of the main channels of the waters listed, except Old Man Creek): the Murrumbidgee River between the Hume Highway road bridge at Gundagai and 100m upstream of the weir face at Berembed Weir near Ganmain, and the Murray River from 130m below Hume Weir near Albury to the Newell Highway road bridge at Tocumwal. All waters are closed to Murray Crayfish fishing at all other times.","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"2","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"10 - 12 cm","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"4","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Crayfish, Other Spiny
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Crayfish, Other Spiny","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Invertebrate","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"9cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"5 (one or more species), only 1 over 12cm","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Euastacus crayfish, also known as spiny crayfish, are widely distributed in Australia living in both cold and warm habitats from far north Queensland to the South Australia \/ Victoria border.  Many spiny crayfish species have a limited distribution and are endemic to certain localities.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Euastacus crayfish species range in size between approximately 4 cm and 12 cm maximum occipital carapace length.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Euastacus crayfish are slow-growing animals taking many years to reach their legal length of 9 cm. Like all other freshwater crayfish species, they undertake a series of moults as they grow. They are late maturing and long lived animals. They are major processors of organic matter acting as shredders, predators, collectors and grazers.  They are an important source of food for other fauna including invertebrates, frogs, fish and platypus.  They also assist in maintaining river health and structure.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Murray Crayfish","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/14\/Spineycrayfish-1460590458304.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"5 (one or more species, only 1 of which can be longer than 12cm), cannot be taken in trout waters.
