name: Freshwater catfish (eel-tailed)
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Freshwater catfish (eel-tailed)","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Threatened Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"30 cm in listed dams, eastern dams and eastern rivers","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"5 in listed dams and eastern dams, 2 in eastern rivers","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Freshwater catfish were formerly very abundant across most of the Murray-Darling Basin in inland New South Wales. Prior to the 1980s, they provided recreational fishing opportunities and they are still considered one of the premier table fish by many country people. However, catfish numbers declined substantially following the invasion of carp during the 1970s and 80s. In addition to carp, thermal pollution and season flow reversal also have major impacts in affected reaches. Catfish have virtually disappeared from the Murray, Murrumbidgee and Lachlan catchments. Catfish are still relatively common in parts of the Macquarie, Namoi, Gwydir and Border River catchments and coastal catchments North of Newcastle.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Can grow up to 900mm and 7kg, however fish over 2kg are exceptional.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Colour ranges from grey to brown dorsally or laterally, usually mottled with dark brown to black blotchings with a whitish underbelly. Larger fish have less mottlings and can be more green in colour fading to white below. It builds a nest in areas of still water to breed, and its reproduction is not temperature reliant. Catfish feed on zooplankton, small fish, shrimps and insects. Catfish are relatively inactive and do not migrate for spawning, unlike other inland species such as trout, golden perch or Murray cod.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Recent electrophoretic studies of proteins of some more northerly populations indicate that catfish inhabiting coastal rivers from the Manning to the Belliger Rivers may be of different species and those from the Nymboida River (Clarence River system) northwards to at least the Tweed River subspecies, different from the widespread inland form.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/5\/3\/Eeltailcatfish-1462234758730.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Restricted areas","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Catfish may be taken all year in eastern rivers, eastern dams and the following listed dams: Pindari, Copeton, Split Rock, Keepit, Chaffey, Glenbawn, Glennies Creek, Windamere, Burrendong, Ben Chifley and Wyangala. Catfish cannot be targeted in western rivers or other western dams.","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"5 in listed dams and eastern dams, 2 in eastern rivers","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"30 cm in listed dams, eastern dams and eastern rivers","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"10 in listed dams and eastern dams, 4 in eastern rivers","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Golden perch
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Golden perch","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"30cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"5","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Golden Perch, also known as Yellowbelly, Callop, Perch, Murray Perch or White Perch, naturally inhabit the Murray-Darling river system (except at high elevations) and exist in the internal drainage systems of Lake Eyre and the Bulloo River. Recent evidence suggests that there may be a genetic difference between populations resulting in the existence of a separate species. The abundance of Golden Perch has dramatically decreased in the Murray-Darling due to migration obstruction and the alteration of flow regimes and temperature stratification following the construction of weirs and dams. Golden Perch have been translocated into other rivers of New South Wales, Queensland and the Northern Territory. They prefer warm, slow moving, turbid streams.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Golden Perch have been recorded up to 76 centimetres in length and 23 kilograms in weight. However, they are commonly measured between 40 and 50 centimetres in length and under 5 kilograms in weight. Those fish stocked in impoundments generally reach larger sizes than those occurring naturally in river systems.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"This species is a member of the family Percichthyidae. Adult perch are moderate to large in size and are bronze, olive green to brownish in colour overall with a yellow ventral surface. The forehead is distinctly concave above the eyes and the lower jaw is protruding. Juvenile Golden Perch feed on zooplankton (microscopic animals) while adults feed on fishes, molluscs and crayfish.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Golden Perch are sometimes confused with Macquarie perch (Macquaria australasica), however golden perch have a concave forehead and protruding lower jaw. Small Golden Perch are also often confused with small Silver Perch, Goldfish, Carp, Murray Cod and Trout Cod.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/14\/Goldenperch-1460608590244.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"5","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"30cm","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"10","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Silver perch
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Silver perch","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Threatened Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"25 cm in listed dams","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"5 in listed dams","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Silver Perch were once widespread and abundant throughout most of the Murray-Darling river system. They have now declined to low numbers or disappeared from most of their former range. Only one remaining secure and self sustaining population occurs in NSW in the central Murray River downstream of Yarrawonga weir, as well as several anabranches and tributaries.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Silver Perch usually reach 30-40 cm and 0.5-1.5 kg, but have been recorded up to 8 kg.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Silver Perch are a moderate to large freshwater fish native to the Murray-Darling river system. Silver Perch are oval shaped with a small head that can become beak-like in larger fish. The colour can be grey, greenish, gold or silvery, darker on the back and paler on the sides, with a white belly. Juveniles may be mottled with vertical dark bars.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Silver Perch closely resemble two other terapontid species found in adjoining drainages of the Murray-Darling system. These are the Welch's Grunter (Bidyanus welchi) and the Barcoo Grunter (Scortum barcoo).","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/14\/Silverperch-1460608562321.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"SILVER PERCH","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Restricted areas","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Silver Perch may only be taken from the following listed dams: Pindari, Copeton, Split Rock, Keepit, Chaffey, Glenbawn, Glennies Creek, Windamere, Burrendong, Ben Chifley, Wyangala, Wyangan, Yass Burrinjuck, Lake Albert, Googong, Blowering and Jounama. Silver Perch cannot be targeted in all other dams and rivers and their tributaries.","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"5 in listed dams","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"25 cm in listed dams","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"10 in listed dams","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Atlantic salmon
content: {"content":[{"key":"Species type","type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER"},{"key":"Fish name","type":"text","value":"Atlantic salmon"},{"key":"Sub header","type":"textarea","value":null},{"key":"Size limit","type":"text","value":"25 cm/50 cm/25 cm"},{"key":"Bag limit","type":"text","value":null},{"key":"About","type":"textarea","value":"A native of European and North American rivers draining into the northern Atlantic Ocean, the Atlantic Salmon has been introduced into Lake Jindabyne and Khancoban Pondage. No wild populations occur since most of the natural life cycle is spent at sea. The Atlantic Salmon is considered a great sport fish and is keenly sought by anglers."},{"key":"Size","type":"textarea","value":"Atlantic Salmon are known to reach in excess of 30kg, however, a fish greater than 6kg in Australia is rare."},{"key":"Characteristics","type":"textarea","value":"Similar to Brown Trout, but silvery overall, bluish to olive-brown dorsally with a white belly and fewer dark spots usually confined to the upper sides. These spots usually lack the halo characteristic of the Brown Trout. The fins are a dusky grey and the fish has a thick wrist of the tail. When compared to the Brown Trout, the mouth of the Atlantic Salmon is smaller and doesn't extend past the eyes and the tail is more deeply forked."},{"key":"Confusing species","type":"textarea","value":"Similar to other trout and salmon species."},{"key":"Media","type":"file","value":"https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/fish-smart-images/images/uploads/2016/5/3/AtlanticsalmonVP-1462234671913.jpg"},{"key":"Grouped","type":"checkbox","value":"1"},{"key":"Group type","type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"TROUT AND SALMON"},{"key":"Group title","type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit and fishing seasons"},{"key":"Group description","type":"textarea","value":"The bag and possession limit is combined for all trout species and salmon and varies depending on the water classification and the open fishing seasons. Waters classified as artificial fly and lure streams and general trout streams are open to fishing from the start of the October long weekend to the end of the June long weekend. All fishing is prohibited in these waters between the end of the June long weekend and start of the October long weekend. Some artificial fly and lure streams revert to trout spawning stream rules from 1 May to the end of the June long weekend. General trout dams and all other waters are open to fishing all year. For more information on trout water classifications see the Freshwater Fishing Guide (accessible in Rules in this app)."},{"key":"Rule bag limit","type":"text","value":"2 (one or more species) in artificial fly and lure streams and dams, 1 (one or more species) in trout spawning streams, 5 (one or more species) in general trout streams, general trout dams and all other waters"},{"key":"Rule legal size","type":"text","value":"25 cm in artificial fly and lure streams and dams, 50 cm in trout spawning streams, 25 cm in general trout streams, general trout dams and all other waters"},{"key":"Rule possession","type":"text","value":"4 (one or more species) in artificial fly and lure streams and dams, 2 (one or more species) in trout spawning streams,  10 (one or more species) in general trout streams, general trout dams and all other waters"}]}

name: Trout, Brown
content: {"content":[{"key":"Species type","type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER"},{"key":"Fish name","type":"text","value":"Trout, Brown"},{"key":"Sub header","type":"textarea","value":null},{"key":"Size limit","type":"text","value":"25 cm/50 cm/25cm *"},{"key":"Bag limit","type":"text","value":"2 (one or more species) in artificial fly and lure streams and dams, 1 (one or more species) in trout spawning streams , 5 (one or more species) general trout dams and  all other waters"},{"key":"About","type":"textarea","value":"Imported from England, the brown trout is possibly the most important sport fish to be introduced in Australia. It is commonly found in cool waters, mostly above 600m, with moderate to swift flow and also in cool, clear lakes and reservoirs."},{"key":"Size","type":"textarea","value":"In Australia they are known to reach at least 90cm and can weigh up to 14kg, but the most commonly caught fish are below 3kg."},{"key":"Characteristics","type":"textarea","value":"The brown trout is a thick bodied species with a large head, mouth and moderate to large eyes. The mouth extends to below the eyes. Colours can vary depending on factors such as age and habitat. Generally silver to olive-brownish and darker along the dorsal area. They display dark spots along the back and sides, but these can sometimes be indistinct. Most spots are surrounded by a pale halo and are often red below the mid-line."},{"key":"Confusing species","type":"textarea","value":"Similar to other trout and salmon species."},{"key":"Media","type":"file","value":"https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/fish-smart-images/images/uploads/2016/4/14/browntroutVP-1460606377403.jpg"},{"key":"Grouped","type":"checkbox","value":"1"},{"key":"Group type","type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"TROUT AND SALMON"},{"key":"Group title","type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit and fishing seasons"},{"key":"Group description","type":"textarea","value":"The bag and possession limit is combined for all trout species and salmon and varies depending on the water classification and the open fishing seasons. name: Trout, Rainbow

name: Yabbies - Freshwater
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Yabbies - Freshwater","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Invertebrate","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"200","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Yabbies  (Cherax destructor) are found in much of central and western NSW, south western Queensland, the majority of Victoria and the eastern part of South Australia. They inhabit freshwater creeks, rivers, lakes, farm dams, swamps, floodplains and irrigation channels. They prefer to occupy turbid shallow water that is slow flowing or still. They can be found at depths up to 5 metres depending on dissolved oxygen concentrations.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Yabbies can reach a carapace (upper shell) length of 7 centimetres or 16 centimetres total body length.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Yabby is a member of the family Parastacidae. They possess broad, spade-like claws, a short smooth rostrum (forward projecting spine between the eyes) and are generally pale to dark brown in colour. Yabbies are vigorous burrowers and are very resilient, being able to withstand poor water quality and long periods of drought. The scientific name \"destructor\" actually refers to the Yabby's tendency to burrow into levee banks and dam walls where they can cause considerable damage. Yabbies are detritus feeders and opportunistic carnivores. They are also cannibalistic.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"None.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/5\/3\/YabbyVP-1462234526682.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"200","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"200","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Crayfish, Fitzroy Falls Spiny
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Crayfish, Fitzroy Falls Spiny","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Threatened Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/a","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Fitzroy Falls Spiny Crayfish (Euastacus dharawalus) is a rare species of Australian crayfish endemic to a small location on the NSW Southern Highlands. The species is only found in Wildes Meadow Creek NSW, surviving as a remnant population, restricted to a small length of the waterway upstream from Fitzroy Falls.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The maximum reported size of the Fitzroy Falls Spiny Crayfish is 86 mm OCL and 300 grams.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Fitzroy Falls Spiny Crayfish is one of over 40 species in the genus Euastacus which represents freshwater 'spiny' crayfish. Euastacus is the second most widely distributed genus of freshwater crayfish in Australia, and contains many species with limited distributions. The Fitzroy Falls Spiny Crayfish is a relatively large, long living, non-aggressive species which is morphologically similar to Euastacus spinifer, the Sydney Spiny Crayfish.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Fitzroy Falls Spiny Crayfish in its natural environment may be confused with the common Yabby (Cherax destructor) which has been translocated to the Wildes Meadow Creek catchment from the Murray-Darling Basin. The Fitzroy Falls Spiny Crayfish can be distinguished by its larger size, and the presence of short robust spikes on its claws, carapace and abdomen while the Yabby is smooth shelled.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Flathead Galaxias
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Flathead Galaxias","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Threatened Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Flathead Galaxias (Galaxias rostratus), also known as Murray jollytail are a small native fish that are known from the southern part of the Murray Darling Basin. They have been recorded in the Macquarie, Lachlan, Murrumbidgee and Murray Rivers in NSW. Despite extensive scientific sampling over the past 15 years there have been very few recorded sightings of Flathead Galaxias. They have not been recorded and are considered locally extinct in the lower Murray, Murrumbidgee, Macquarie and Lachlan Rivers. The species is now only known from the upper Murray River near Tintaldra and wetland areas near Howlong.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Flathead Galaxias grow to about 150mm in length.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"They are olive green with a silver belly, transparent fins and a slight mottled appearance on their upper sides and back. They have a forked tail, long slender body and a large mouth that extends back to below the eye.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Flathead Galaxias are similar in appearance to the common jollytail, Galaxias maculatus, although the distinctive flat head of Galaxias rostratus is a distinguishing feature.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule possession"}]}

content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Murray Hardyhead","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Threatened Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Murray Hardyhead (Craterocephalus fluviatilis) is a species of small freshwater fish, native to inland parts of south-eastern Australia. name: Macquarie Perch
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Macquarie Perch","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Threatened Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Macquarie Perch (Macquaria australasica) are found in the Murray-Darling Basin (particularly upstream reaches) of the Lachlan, Murrumbidgee and Murray rivers, and parts of south-eastern coastal NSW, including the Hawkesbury\/Nepean and Shoalhaven catchments. The conservation status of the different populations is not well known, but there have been long-term declines in their abundance.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Macquarie Perch are an elongated, oval shaped fish with large eyes and a rounded tail. Some clear differences have been shown between eastern (coastal) and western (Murray-Darling) populations, but so far they haven't been described as separate species. Macquarie Perch from the Murray-Darling Basin are larger, growing up to 46 cm and 3.5 kg (though they are more commonly less than 1.5 kg). They can be black, silver-grey, blue-grey or green-brown in colour, with a paler underside. Macquarie Perch from coastal catchments are distinctly smaller (usually less than 18 cm in length) and are blotched with grey-brown, buff and dark grey patches over the head and body.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Australian Bass.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/14\/Macquarieperch-1460604354013.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Oxleyan Pygmy Perch
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Oxleyan Pygmy Perch","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Threatened Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Oxleyan Pygmy Perch (Nannoperca oxleyana) are a small freshwater fish endemic to the coastal region of eastern Australia, from northern NSW to south-eastern Queensland. They also occur on Fraser, Moreton and Stradbroke Islands. They have specific habitat requirements and are patchily distributed within this range.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"They can grow to about 60mm in length, but are more commonly found to lengths of about 35mm.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Oxleyan Pygmy Perch are light brown to olive in colour (darker on the back and paler on the sides) with three to four patchy brown bars running from head to tail. There is a dark spot with an orange rim at the base of the tail and a blue ring around the eye. During breeding the fins darken and the lateral stripes and tail turn red.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"None.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/14\/OxyleanpygmyperchVP-1460604489482.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Purple Spotted Gudgeon
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Purple Spotted Gudgeon","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Threatened Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Purple Spotted Gudgeons (Mogurnda adspersa) occur in inland drainages of the Murray-Darling basin as well as coastal drainages of northern NSW and Queensland. The western population of the Purple Spotted Gudgeon was previously widespread in the Murray, Murrumbidgee and Lachlan River systems and tributaries of the Darling, but has experienced a significant decline in recent times. Purple Spotted Gudgeons are now extremely rare in inland NSW, having been recorded from this area only once since 1983.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Purple Spotted Gudgeons generally grow to between 7 and 12 cm in length.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Purple Spotted Gudgeons are small and robust with a rounded head, a relatively small mouth and a rounded tail. They are generally dark chocolate in colour along the back, fading to pale fawn on the belly, with a number of distinguishing markings. These include black to grey patches on the sides, which are surrounded by numerous white and red spots that brighten during breeding. The fins are yellow in colour, darkening towards the extremities.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/5\/17\/Purplespotgudg(JHdrawg)_nobkg-1463459264562.tif","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Tuna, Southern Bluefin
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Tuna, Southern Bluefin","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Southern Bluefin Tuna (Thunnus maccoyii) are highly migratory pelagic fish. In Australian waters they range from northern NSW around southern Australia to northwestern Australia. They tend to form large surface schools in offshore waters off southern Australia at certain times of the year. Overfishing has drastically reduced its numbers.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Southern Bluefin Tuna can reach a maximum length of 2.35 metres and can attain a weight of around 200kg, but don't often exceed 100kg in Australian waters.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Southern Bluefin Tuna are a member of the family Scombridae and are recognised by their relatively short pectoral fins and robust body. name: Southern Pygmy Perch
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Southern Pygmy Perch","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Threatened Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Southern Pygmy Perch (Nannoperca australis) were once widely distributed throughout the Murrumbidgee and Murray River systems, as well as coastal streams in South Australia and Victoria, north-eastern Tasmania and King and Flinders Islands in Bass Strait. There have been large-scale reductions in their range since European settlement, particularly in inland regions. Populations of Southern Pygmy Perch have recently been discovered in tributaries of the upper Lachlan and upper Murray River catchments.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Southern Pygmy Perch are small fish, growing to approximately 65-85 mm in length.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"They have a small mouth reaching to just below the eye, and a rounded tail. The colour varies greatly depending upon where the fish live and the environmental conditions present there. The base colour ranges from pale cream to green-brown, darker on the back and paler on the belly. There are often irregular markings on the sides, but these are also very variable; some fish may be almost plain while others have dark spots or even longitudinal bands. Breeding males display brighter colours, with the dorsal and anal fins becoming bright red with black edges, and the region around the vent and on the breast and chin turning black.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/5\/17\/southernpygmyperch-1463459315806.bmp","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Trout Cod
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Trout Cod","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Threatened Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Trout Cod (Maccullochella macquariensis) is endemic to the southern Murray-Darling river system, including the Murrumbidgee and Murray Rivers, and the Macquarie River in central NSW. The species was once widespread and abundant in these areas but has undergone dramatic declines in its distribution and abundance over the past century. The last known reproducing population of Trout Cod is confined to the Murray River below Yarrawonga downstream to Tocumwal.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Trout Cod can grow to 85cm and 16kg, but are more common to 50cm and 1.5kg.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Trout Cod is a large, deep-bodied species that has a big mouth and a straight head profile. It can be recognised by its overhanging upper jaw and the presence of a dusky horizontal stripe from the snout, through the eyes and onto the preoperculum. The fish is bluish grey or brown, with irregular spots and bars on the upper and lateral surfaces of the body as well as on the soft dorsal, anal and caudal fins. It is pale ventrally. ","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Murray Cod.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/13\/Troutcod2-1460523438736.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"TROUT COD","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Trout Cod cannot be targeted in NSW waters other than for catch and release fishing in Talbingo Dam. To protect breeding Trout Cod, the Murray River between Yarrawonga Weir and the Tocumwal Road Bridge is closed to fishing from 1 September to 30 November each year.","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Ballina Angelfish
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Ballina Angelfish","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Protected Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Ballina angelfish occur in northern NSW around Coffs Harbour, Ballina and North Solitary Islands, and around the Balls Pyramid area of Lord Howe Island. name: Eastern Blue Devil
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Eastern Blue Devil","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Protected Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Eastern blue devil fish, Paraplesiops bleekeri, also known as Bleakers blue devil fish, are a shy, secretive fish found in caves, crevices and under ledges on inshore reefs and estuaries. Eastern blue devil fish are distributed from southern Queensland to Montague Island on the NSW south coast.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The fish grows to 40 cm in length.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Eastern blue devil fish are most easily recognised by their banded pattern of blue and white stripes on the body, blue spotted head, blue dorsal and anal fins, and yellow tail fin and base and pectoral fins. The pelvic fins and rear dorsal and anal fins are elongated. When blue devil fish spread these fins they overlap, making the fish appear larger. \r\nJuveniles are generally a less colourful dusky brown with less prominent stripes or general blue colouration. name: Elegant Wrasse
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Elegant Wrasse","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Protected Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Elegant wrasse are a widespread but uncommon species found on coral reef and rocky reef habitats at depths from 2 to 35 m. The distribution of elegant wrasse extends from southern Queensland to Montague Island on the NSW south coast, particularly around inshore islands. The species is also found at Lord Howe Island, especially in the shallow lagoon habitat, and at nearby Elizabeth and Middleton Reefs. Elegant wrasse have also been recorded from Norfolk Island, the Kermadec Islands, New Zealand and other distant locations in the Pacific Ocean including Easter Island. Elegant wrasse are a subtropical, warm-temperate species that are active during the day.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Elegant wrasse grow to approximately 30 cm in length.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"They have several colour forms and their appearance is reported to vary with age and size. name: Ghostpipefish
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Ghostpipefish","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Protected Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Ghostpipefish are closely related to the seahorse, seadragon, pipefish, and pipehorses but differ in that all ghostpipefish fins are well developed and large. Ghostpipefish are perhaps the most spectacular of the syngnathiformes in appearance, with some species, such as the Ornate Ghostpipefish Solenostomus paradoxus, displaying elaborate colours and bony spines. Other species such as the robust or rough snout ghostpipefish Solenostomus cyanopterus and S. paegnius, are less elaborate and adopt the colours of the algae or seagrasses with which they associate. These species are found in NSW in habitats ranging from muddy open bottoms to reefs with rich invertebrate life, usually in sheltered coastal or estuary waters. Ghostpipefish like seahorses and pipefish have an elongated snout that they use to feed on small shrimp-like crustaceans.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Goldspotted Rockcod (Estuary cod)
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Goldspotted Rockcod (Estuary cod)","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Protected Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Goldspotted Rockcod\/ Estuary cod (Epinephelus coioides) occur in tropical and warm temperate marine waters of the Indo-Pacific including the Persian Gulf, India, the Philippines, Singapore, Hong Kong, Taiwan, Fiji and around numerous other islands. In Australia they are most common in Queensland, the Northern Territory and Western Australia; however, they are known to occur as far southwards as the Sydney area.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The species grows to 1 m in length","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Goldspotted Rockcod\/ Estuary cod inhabit turbid coastal reefs and are often found in brackish water over mud and rubble. They are frequently misidentified as Epinephelus tauvina (Greasy grouper) or Epinephelus malabaricus (Malabar grouper), which look similar and have overlapping distributions. Estuary cod also have a variety of common names including estuary rock cod, orange-spotted grouper, orange-spotted cod, green grouper, greasy cod, spotted river cod and brown-spotted grouper.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/14\/estuarycodV05-1460607906474.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Queensland groper
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Queensland groper","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Protected Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Queensland groper (or grouper), also known as the giant groper or Queensland groper, is one of the largest reef-dwelling fish in the world. They have a wide distribution throughout the tropical waters of the Indo-West Pacific. In Australia they occur along all tropical and warm temperate coasts but are rarely found in cooler waters to the south.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Queensland gropers are one of the largest of all bony fishes, reaching lengths of up to 3 m and weighing about 600 kg.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Juveniles have a large blotched and banded pattern, but as adults become mottled and spotted to evenly dark grey or brownish. The mottled colouration blends with the surroundings, providing good camouflage for\r\nambush hunting. They have a rounded tail. Adult giant Queensland gropers\u2019 stocky shape and brown colouration give them a nearly potato-like profile as they rest motionless on the bottom or hover in mid-water, using only tiny fin movements to maintain their position.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/19\/groperqldV05-1461043374956.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"0 ","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Shark, Herbsts Nurse
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Shark, Herbsts Nurse","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Protected Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Herbsts nurse sharks are a rarely encountered species that looks very similar to the grey nurse shark. Grey nurse sharks are found in shallower inshore waters, while Herbsts nurse sharks are generally found at depths of 150\u2013600 m off the NSW coast. The species has a wide but irregular distribution throughout the warm temperate and tropical waters of the Atlantic, Indian and Pacific oceans, and the Mediterranean Sea. In Australasia, they have been recorded off NSW, eastern Victoria, north-western Australia, New Zealand and the Kermadec Islands.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Herbsts nurse shark is a large shark growing to about 4.5 m in length and over 700 kg in weight.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Herbsts nurse sharks are large, bulky sharks  with a long, conical snout. They are medium to dark grey above, fading to white on the belly. Juveniles may have dusky margins and tips on both dorsal fins and the tail fin, sometimes with darker spots scattered on the flanks. The first dorsal fin is bigger than both the second dorsal fin and the anal fin, a feature that distinguishes them from grey nurse sharks, which have two dorsal fins of similar size.\r\nHerbsts nurse sharks can also be distinguished from grey nurse sharks by their teeth. Herbsts nurse sharks have slender fang-like teeth with two or three pairs of small lateral cusplets near the base of each tooth, whereas grey nurse sharks have a single pair of lateral cusplets on each tooth.\r\nThe origin of the Herbsts nurse shark\u2019s first dorsal fin is over the free rear end of pectorals, and the front of the second dorsal fin is above the back of the pelvic fins. A notch is present immediately in front of the tail.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/19\/herbstnurseV05-1461043324428.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Seahorses, Pipefish, Seadragons etc
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Seahorses, Pipefish, Seadragons etc","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Syngnathiformes - Protected Species","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Some of the most decorative and elusive fish in NSW waters belong to the families 'Syngnathidae', 'Solenostomidae' and 'Pegasidae'. These unique and delicate groups of fish include seahorses, seadragons, pipefish, pipehorses, ghostpipefish and seamoths, known collectively as 'Syngnathiformes'. All Syngnathiformes are protected species in NSW.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Syngnathiformes are distinct in appearance compared to their other bony fish relatives. There are many distinguishing morphological, behavioural and reproductive features that separate the seahorse, seadragon, pipefish, pipehorse, ghostpipefish and seamoth families.\r\n\r\nDepending on the surrounding environment, syngnathiformes can be highly variable in colour and shape. Some syngnathiformes have the ability to change colour in minutes or to grow additional skin to mimic seagrasses and seaweeds they inhabit. This characteristic is a major defence and feeding strategy. Their small fins restrict them to slow movement giving them little opportunity to escape from predators, or to actively chase their prey when feeding.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/19\/WeedyseadragonFMV05-1461043218302.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"AUSTRALIAN BASSN ESTUARY PERCH","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit and closed season","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Australian Bass and Estuary Perch have a combined bag limit of 2 in total, with a possession limit of 4 in total. name: Shark, Wobbegong
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Shark, Wobbegong","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"0","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Wobbegong sharks occur along the east coast from southern Queensland through to Western Australia, including Tasmania. They inhabit shallow, inshore waters (less than 100 metres deep) where rock and weed are prominent.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Reaches a length of 3 metres and a weight of over 70kg.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The head & body are various shades of brown forming mottled patterns, and they have numerous skin flaps around the mouth. Wobbegong sharks can become aggressive if disturbed, and are able to reach back and bite a hand holding their tail.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"There are two species of wobbegong shark commonly found in coastal waters of New South Wales: the banded (pictured) and the spotted wobbegong. content: {"content":[{"key":"Species type","type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER"},{"key":"Fish name","type":"text","value":"Shark, Mako"},{"key":"Sub header","type":"textarea","value":null},{"key":"Size limit","type":"text","value":"N/A"},{"key":"Bag limit","type":"text","value":"1"},{"key":"About","type":"textarea","value":"The Mako Shark is an offshore species found in tropical and warm temperate seas in waters generally over 16C and occurring from the surface to depths of at least 150m."},{"key":"Size","type":"textarea","value":"Maximum size up to around 4m in length."},{"key":"Characteristics","type":"textarea","value":"The Mako has a spindle-shaped body with a long, acutely conical snout and large blade-like teeth that lack serrations and are always visible. name: Trevallies
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Trevallies","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"30 cm (Silver Trevally only)","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"10 in total*. 20 in possession.","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Giant trevally, Silver Trevally, Gold Spotted Trevally, Banded Trevally, Blue Trevally, Thicklip Trevally, Bluefin Trevally, Bigeye Trevally, Golden Trevally, Sand Trevally, Diamond Trevally. Trevally species are commonly found along the New South Wales Coast. The species more common in NSW include the Silver Trevally, Bluefin Trevally and Bigeye Trevally. They are found on inshore reefs and around estuary systems and can form large schools. Species such as Silver Trevally can be found in large schools in offshore waters. At least 23 species of trevally are found along the east coast of Australia.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Maximum length for a Silver Trevally is approximately 1.4m compared to the maximum length of Giant Trevally that is around 1.7m. The larger trevally species can grow up to 2 metres and about 80kg.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The trevallies are actively swimming, highly streamlined fishes with very fine scales. The most prominent features in trevally are the forked caudal or tail fin and the ridge of plates on each side of the base of the tail. name: Tuna, Yellowfin
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Tuna, Yellowfin","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"90 cm or above - 2 in total,  Less than 90 cm - 5 in total","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"90 cm or above - 2 in total,  Less than 90 cm - 5 in total","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Yellowfin tuna, also known as yellowfin or Allison tuna, are oceanic fish found in Australian waters from Torres Strait to eastern Tasmania and from the Northern Territory to south-western Australia. They may also be found in the brackish waters of estuaries. Sea surface temperature, salinity and dissolved oxygen concentration limit the distribution of yellowfin tuna. ","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Yellowfin tuna reach a maximum length of 2.1 metres and weigh 175 kilograms. Yellowfin tuna caught off eastern Australia rarely exceed 190 cm in length and 100 kilograms in weight.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Yellowfin tuna are a member of the family Scombridae. These heavy-bodied fish are recognised by their bright yellow dorsal and anal fins and finlets. They have a dark blue back and a vivid broad golden yellow stripe that runs from eye to tail. They also have moderately long pectoral fins. Adult yellowfin are opportunistic carnivores that feed on squid, skipjack tuna, smaller yellowfin tuna, mackerel, pilchards and pelagic crabs.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Yellowfin tuna that have a fork length less than 75 centimetres can be difficult to distinguish from small bigeye tuna (Thunnus obesus).","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/14\/YellowFinTunaV05-1460596162153.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"TUNA","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Combined group bag limit of 2 in total 90cm or above, if less than 90cm then  5 in total. name: Abalone
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Abalone","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Invertebrate","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"11.7cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"2","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Blacklip abalone (also known as brownlip abalone) are endemic to Australia and are found from mid NSW down and along the southern coastline to Rottnest Island in Western Australia. They are also found in the coastal waters of Tasmania. Abalone adhere to rocky services and inhabit crevices and caves on reefs. They generally inhabit waters between 5 and 10 metres in depth, but can be found in deeper waters up to 40 metres in depth.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Blacklip abalone can grow to 21 centimetres in length.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Blacklip abalone is a member of the family Haliotidae. They possess a single, ear-shaped shell lined with mother of pearl and spirally ridged on the outside. The foot of the abalone has a distinct black lip giving the species its name. Blacklip abalone feed on drift algae and graze on seagrass leaves and algae growing on rocks. Their diet is predominantly comprised of red algae.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/6\/15\/021517-1465949553509.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"AUSTRALIAN BASSN ESTUARY PERCH","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit and closed season","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Australian Bass and Estuary Perch have a combined bag limit of 2 in total, with a possession limit of 4 in total. name: Balmain Bug
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Balmain Bug","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Invertebrate","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"10cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"20","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Balmain Bugs, also known as slipper lobsters and shovelnose lobsters, are distributed throughout the southern half of Australia from Queensland to Western Australia. They inhabit soft sand and muddy environments in water depths ranging from 15 to 650 metres, but found most commonly at depths of 150 metres.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Balmain Bugs can reach a total length of over 25 centimetres and a weight of around 400 grams.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Balmain Bugs are members of the family Scyllaridae and are characterised by their broad, flat shaped bodies and large carapace. The species also possesses broad but short, flattened antennae and five pairs of legs. name: Crab, Blue Swimmer
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Crab, Blue Swimmer","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Invertebrate","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"6cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"10","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Blue swimmer crabs are found in coastal waters from Cape Naturaliste in Western Australia, around the top end to NSW. The Victorian border is the southern limit for distribution of the species on the east coast.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Maximum length of about 21cm across the carapace (shell), and a weight of up to 1kg.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Blue swimmer crabs, also known as sand crabs or blue manna crabs, are swimming crabs that have their last pair of legs modified to act as paddles. Their claws are long and slender and the shell is rough in texture. The carapace is broad, with a prominent spine on each side. The colours vary from dark brown, blue and purple, with pale mottling. Adult crabs are frequently found in large numbers in shallow bays and estuaries, particularly during the summer months. Blue swimmer crabs are highly regarded for their taste.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/14\/BlueswimmercrabV05-1460607486577.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"10","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"6cm","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"20","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Crab, Mud
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Crab, Mud","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Invertebrate","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"8.5cm","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"5","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Mud Crab inhabit tropical to warm temperate waters from Exmouth in Western Australia up and along the coastline of the Northern Territory and Queensland to the Bega River in southern New South Wales. They favour soft muddy bottoms below the low tide level and generally live in sheltered estuaries, mud flats, mangrove forests and the tidal reaches of some rivers.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Mud Crab can reach a maximum size of approximately 24 centimetres carapace width and 3.5 kilograms in weight.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Mud Crab are a member of the family Portunidae. They are large crabs with a smooth, broad carapace and possess sizeable claws used for crushing and cutting prey. The two hind legs are flattened for swimming. Mud Crab are generally very dark brown to mottled green in colour. Juvenile's feed on planktonic animals, benthic molluscs and crustaceans while adults feed on bivalve and gastropod molluscs (mussels and pipis), small crabs and polychaete worms.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/14\/Mudcrab-1460607467919.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"5","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"8.5cm","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"5","key":"Rule possession"}]}
