name: Lobster, Eastern Rock
content: {"content":[{"key":"Species type","type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER"},{"key":"Fish name","type":"text","value":"Lobster, Eastern Rock"},{"key":"Sub header","type":"textarea","value":"Invertebrate"},{"key":"Size limit","type":"text","value":"10.4-18cm"},{"key":"Bag limit","type":"text","value":"2 in total in any combination of lobsters"},{"key":"About","type":"textarea","value":"Eastern Rock Lobsters inhabit the continental shelf along the east coast of Australia, from Tweed Heads in New South Wales, around Tasmania, through to Port MacDonnell in South Australia. They hide in holes and crevices around rocky areas and reefs, preferring vegetative cover such as weed/kelp."},{"key":"Size","type":"textarea","value":"Maximum weight of 8kg and a carapace length of 26cm (1m including the antennas)."},{"key":"Characteristics","type":"textarea","value":"Eastern Rock Lobster have a green body and brownish-orange legs. Their abdominal segments are smooth and unsculptured on their dorsal surface. They generally move into deeper water in early winter, and return closer to the shoreline in late August."},{"key":"Confusing species","type":"textarea","value":"In the south of the state the Southern Rock Lobster (Jasus edwardsii) is found. Eastern Rock Lobsters are green in colour, Southern Lobsters are red. In the north of the state the Ornate Rock Lobster (Panulirus ornatus) occurs. Ornate Lobsters are greenish blue to reddish brown in colour, with orange spines on the head."},{"key":"Media","type":"file","value":"https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/fish-smart-images/images/uploads/2016/6/15/021531-1465956089715.jpg"},{"key":"Grouped","type":"checkbox","value":"1"},{"key":"Group type","type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER"},{"key":"Group title","type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit"},{"key":"Group description","type":"textarea","value":"Eastern and Southern Rock Lobsters have a combined bag limit of 2 in total."},{"key":"Rule bag limit","type":"text","value":"2 in total (with Southern Rock Lobster, in any combination of lobsters)"},{"key":"Rule legal size","type":"text","value":"Min 10.4, Max 18cm"},{"key":"Rule possession","type":"text","value":"2 in total (with Southern Rock Lobster, in any combination of lobsters)"}]}

name: Lobster, Southern Rock
content: {"content":[{"key":"Species type","type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER"},{"key":"Fish name","type":"text","value":"Lobster, Southern Rock"},{"key":"Sub header","type":"textarea","value":"Invertebrate"},{"key":"Size limit","type":"text","value":"11cm - Males, 10.5cm - Females"},{"key":"Bag limit","type":"text","value":"2 in total in any combination of lobsters"},{"key":"About","type":"textarea","value":"Southern Rock Lobsters are distributed from northern NSW, around Tasmania and across South Australia into Western Australia. They are also found in New Zealand waters. They inhabit a variety of reef habitats in waters ranging from 1 metre to approximately 200 metres in depth."},{"key":"Size","type":"textarea","value":"Adult Southern rock lobsters can reach up to 23 centimetres in length, measured along the carapace. Males tend to be slightly larger than females."},{"key":"Characteristics","type":"textarea","value":"Southern Rock Lobster is a member of the family Palinuridae. They possess two distinct, long supraorbital spines on the upper anterior part of the carapace (upper shell). The carapace also has numerous small spines that are raised and narrow. They range in colour from a reddish-purple and orange in shallower waters to purple and yellow in deeper waters. The species is carnivorous feeding on molluscs, small crustaceans, echinoderms (sea-urchins and sea-stars) and other benthic (bottom dwelling) organisms."},{"key":"Confusing species","type":"textarea","value":""},{"key":"Media","type":"file","value":"https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/fish-smart-images/images/uploads/2016/6/15/022887-1465956821078.jpg"},{"key":"Grouped","type":"checkbox","value":"1"},{"key":"Group type","type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER"},{"key":"Group title","type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit"},{"key":"Group description","type":"textarea","value":"Eastern and Southern Rock Lobsters have a combined bag limit of 2 in total."},{"key":"Rule bag limit","type":"text","value":"2 in total (with Eastern Rock Lobster, in any combination of lobsters)"},{"key":"Rule legal size","type":"text","value":"11cm - Males, 10.5cm - Females"},{"key":"Rule possession","type":"text","value":"2 in total (with Eastern Rock Lobster, in any combination of lobsters)"}]}

name: Lobster (Painted and Ornate), Tropical Rock
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Lobster (Painted and Ornate), Tropical Rock","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Invertebrate","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"2 in total","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The  Tropical Rock Lobster (Painted and Ornate) is found from north-western Australia (Ningaloo region), across northern Australia, down as far south as Sydney on the east coast (been recorded as far south as Albany on the west coast). Lives in depths of 1 to 200 metres (most common in depths of 20 metres), inhabiting a range of reef habitats along the continental shelf, often in caves, holes and crevices.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Fast growing, to 20cm carapace length (50cm total length).","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Tropical Rock Lobster\u2019s colour varies from a greenish blue to reddish brown and they have extremely long and flexible antennae. Each of the abdominal segments are smooth and have large pale spots on either side (2nd to 4th segment have an extra spot) and their eyes are surrounded by blue and pink rings.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Very similar to the Western Rock Lobster (Panulirus cygnum) however this species does not occur on the east coast. Range overlaps with the Eastern Rock Lobster (Jasus verreauxi) but is easily distinguished by colouration and the presence of two very long forked antennules located between the antennae. These are not present on the Eastern Rock Lobster.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/6\/15\/021549-1465956191306.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Tropical Rock Lobster (Painted and Ornate) have a combined bag limit of 2 in total.","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"2. name: Lobster, Slipper (Flat)
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Lobster, Slipper (Flat)","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Invertebrate","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"2","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"There are two main species of Slipper Lobster found in Australian waters, the aesop slipper lobster (S. haanii) and blunt slipper lobster (S. squammosus). Both are also commonly known as flat lobsters or slipper bugs. Slipper lobsters are found on both the east and west coasts. They are not regularly commercially fished, however they may be caught and marketed as part of the prawn trawl fishery bycatch. Found in depths up to 135 metres but can be found as shallow as 10 metres.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Carapace length to over 21cm (over 50.5cm total length).","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Both species are easily distinguishable. The aesop has pronounced bumps along its abdomen, where as the Blunt Slipper Lobster has much less obvious bumps. Very different from other rock lobsters (ornate, eastern & southern) with the main distinguishing feature being the Slipper Lobsters antennae, which have evolved into short, broad, plate-like flat antennae, rather than the long thin antennae of the other rock lobsters.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Slipper Lobsters are often confused with Balmain Bugs (Ibacus species) and Moreton bay Bugs (Thenus species). name: Oysters (Sydney Rock, Pacific, Native)
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Oysters (Sydney Rock, Pacific, Native)","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Invertebrate","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"50 in total","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Sydney Rock Oysters are endemic to Australia and inhabit sheltered estuaries and bays, from Hervey Bay in Queensland to Wingan Inlet in Victoria. The Pacific Oyster is endemic to Japan, but has been introduced into a number of other countries including Australia. It was deliberately introduced into Tasmania, Victoria, Western Australia and South Australia and has spread to NSW and southern Queensland. Adult oysters are sessile and will settle on any hard substrate in the intertidal and shallow subtidal zones, to a depth of about 3 metres. They favour brackish waters in sheltered estuaries, however Pacific oysters can tolerate a large range of salinities and water quality.  The flat or native oyster is found throughout the marine and estuarine habitats of southern Australia, from mid NSW to the southern parts of Western Australia and Tasmania. They usually attach themselves to hard substrates before later breaking free to settle on sand or soft mud. These oysters live in the subtidal zone from about 2 to 20 metres depth.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Sydney Rock Oysters reach approximately 60g in 3 years, and have been known to live for up to 10 years. Pacific Oysters reach a marketable size of 50 grams in 10 months to 2 years. The flat oyster can attain around 25 centimetres in diameter, but are commonly less than 10 centimetres.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Sydney Rock Oysters possess a smooth, thick shell with small teeth on the internal rim of the shell, generally near the hinge. The mantle edges and the adductor muscle scar are pale in colour. The Pacific Oyster is a member of the family Ostreidae and possesses a relatively thin shell with no hinge teeth on the inner, upper shell. The adductor muscle (the muscle which holds the two shells together) is purple or brown in colour, whilst the edges of the mantle (the tissue which secretes and lines the shell) are black. The Pacific Oyster has a very high growth rate and rate of reproduction. They are plankton feeders, filtering algae from the water. Flat oysters are bivalve molluscs belonging to the family Ostreidae. They are roughly egg-shaped with valves of unequal size and shape. The shell margin is slightly irregular and is white or cream in colour on the inner surface and purplish-green to olive-brown or gray on the outer shell surface. They are plankton feeders, filtering algae from the water.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The introduced Pacific Oyster (Crassostrea gigas) is now found throughout most of the range of the Sydney Rock Oyster. The Pacific Oyster has a thin, rough shell with no hinge teeth on the upper shell, the mantle edges are black and the adductor muscle scar is purple\/brown in colour. The environment in which an oyster lives can largely determine its shape (ie. they can be irregular in shape when attached to hard rocky bottoms or very flat when found in soft bottoms). This sometimes makes it difficult to identify oyster species. To distinguish and classify oyster species it is often useful to examine the internal  characteristics.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/20\/022885-1461130340281.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"1","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"OYSTERS","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Oysters have a combined bag limit of 50 in total (in any combination of Sydney Rock, Pacific or Native)","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"50 in total","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"50 in total","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Jack Mackerel and Yellowtail Scad
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"SALTWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Jack Mackerel and Yellowtail Scad","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":null,"key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"50 for each species or species grouping","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"The Yellowtail Scad can be recognised by its silvery colour, tinged with green or brown dorsally, and yellow tail. It is often caught from wharves by anglers.  The Yellowtail Scad is a common schooling species of Australia's southern marine waters from Wide Bay, Queensland to north-west Cape, Western Australia.  The Common Jack Mackerel has an elongate body and a forked caudal fin. The scales in both the curved and straight parts of the lateral line are enlarged and scute-like, but may be overgrown by smaller scales in larger individuals. An accessory lateral line runs close to the base of the dorsal fin as far posteriorly as the fifth to tenth dorsal fin ray. The first dorsal fin is shot-based with eight spines. The second dorsal fin is long-based with the terminal ray being enlarged and slightly separated from the rest of the fin. The species is dark blue-green above and silver to grey below. There is a prominent black blotch on the rear of the operculum. Jack Mackerel is a pelagic species that occurs in Australia and New Zealand. In Australia it is known from southern Queensland, around the south of the country, and north to the central coast of Western Australia. ","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Yellowtail scad grows to 50 cm in length but is usually seen at about 30cm. Jack mackerel grows to at least 60 cm in length.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Yellowtail scad is recognised by its silvery colour, tinged with green or brown dorsally, and yellow tail. It has a distinct dark spot on the rear margin of the operculum. It has enlarged scales, called scutes along the entire lateral line. The pectoral fin is sickle-shaped, or falcate, the caudal peduncle is very shallow and the tail is strongly forked. ","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Common Jack Mackerel is longer and more slender than the Yellowtail Scad and has a longer accessory lateral line (only reaches to below the first or second dorsal fin ray in the Yellowtail Scad). name: Carp
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Carp","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Pest fish","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"-","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Carp are a large introduced freshwater fish which are common throughout most of NSW. They are well known as a pest because of their destructive bottom-feeding habits, which stir up sediments and muddy the water. Over the years carp have been the focus of countless control efforts by government bodies and concerned members of the community.\r\nUnfortunately, any pest as widespread and abundant as carp is impossible to eradicate completely. All the same, many people around the State are involved in programs to tackle this noxious pest and help restore waterways to tip the balance in favour of native fish.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Carp are reported to grow to over one metre in length, and 60 kg in weight. In Australia, this species reaches 10 kg, but 4-5 kg is more usual. ","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Carp can be recognised by its small eyes, thick lips with two barbels at each corner of the mouth, large scales and strongly serrated spines in the dorsal and anal fins. The colour is variable, but often olive green to silvery grey dorsally, fading to silvery yellow on the belly. ","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Small European Carp could be confused with Goldfish, Carassius auratus. name: Redfin perch
content: {"content":[{"type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER","key":"Species type"},{"type":"text","value":"Redfin perch","key":"Fish name"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Pest fish","key":"Sub header"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Size limit"},{"type":"text","value":"-","key":"Bag limit"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Redfin Perch (Redfin), also known as English Perch, is a medium sized freshwater fish native to northern Europe. Redfin were first introduced to Australia in the 1860s for angling, and are now widespread across much of NSW, ACT, Victoria, Tasmania, south-eastern South Australia and the south-western corner of Western Australia.\r\nRedfin are a popular sport fish with some anglers because of their fighting qualities and taste. However, they are also voracious predators of other fish and invertebrates, can destroy recreational fisheries in enclosed waters by building up large numbers of stunted fish and eliminating other species, and can devastate native fish populations by carrying the epizootic haematopoietic necrosis (EHN) virus. For these reasons, Redfin are considered a serious pest and in December 2010 Redfin were listed as a Class 1 noxious species in NSW meaning that it is illegal to be in possession of live Redfin in NSW. It also illegal to use live or dead Redfin as bait in NSW.","key":"About"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Redfin can grow to 60 cm in length and around 10 kg in weight, but are more commonly found up to 45 cm and 1-2 kg.","key":"Size"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Redfin belong to the family Percidae. They have a deep body and a slightly forked tail. They have two distinctly separate dorsal fins, the first with 12-17 strong spines and a distinct black blotch at the rear. They have a pattern of five or more broad black vertical bands across the back, tapering on the sides (more prominent in younger fish). The pelvic and anal fins and tail are bright reddish-orange. The body colour varies from olive green to grey on the back, fading to greenish or silvery on the sides and whitish on the belly.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"None.","key":"Confusing species"},{"type":"file","value":"https:\/\/s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com\/fish-smart-images\/images\/uploads\/2016\/4\/19\/Redfin(Englishperch)VP-1461037022543.jpg","key":"Media"},{"type":"checkbox","value":"0","key":"Grouped"},{"type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"","key":"Group type"},{"type":"text","value":"","key":"Group title"},{"type":"textarea","value":"","key":"Group description"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule bag limit"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule legal size"},{"type":"text","value":"N\/A","key":"Rule possession"}]}

name: Australian Bass
content: {"content":[{"key":"Species type","type":"select[SALTWATER,FRESHWATER]","value":"FRESHWATER"},{"key":"Fish name","type":"text","value":"Australian Bass"},{"key":"Sub header","type":"textarea","value":null},{"key":"Size limit","type":"text","value":"Only 1 over 35cm in rivers"},{"key":"Bag limit","type":"text","value":null},{"key":"About","type":"textarea","value":"Bass are found in fresh and saltwater, in eastern draining rivers from the Mary River in Queensland to the Gippsland Lakes in Victoria."},{"key":"Size","type":"textarea","value":"Maximum of 4kg and 65cm in length."},{"key":"Characteristics","type":"textarea","value":"Bass vary in colour from silver, green and bronze. The fish migrate downstream to the estuaries to breed between June and August and a fishing closure has been introduced at this time, to protect this species. Females are much larger than males. Adult fish are general purpose carnivores. The Bass has a back profile that is arched from above the eyes to the tail with only very slight tapering of the snout. They are sought after sport fish with bait, fly and artificial lures. Although considered excellent eating, the majority of fish are returned to the water unharmed."},{"key":"Confusing species","type":"textarea","value":"Confused with the Estuary Perch (Macquaria colonorum) which has a longer tapered snout with a concave profile."},{"key":"Media","type":"file","value":"https://s3-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com/fish-smart-images/images/uploads/2016/8/10/Austbass1-1470789457919.jpg"},{"key":"Grouped","type":"checkbox","value":"1"},{"key":"Group type","type":"select[AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH,DEEPSEA FISH,BREAM AND TARWHINE,FLOUNDERN SOLE,FLATHEAD,GROPER BLUE RED BROWN,MACKEREL,SAMSONFISH AND AMBERJACK,TUNA,SHARKS AND RAYS,TROUT AND SALMON,MAHI MAHI,MURRAY CRAYFISH,DOGFISH,BAITFISH,LEATHER JACKETS,MULLET,MULLET JUVENILE,TREVALLIES,WHITING,BEACH WORMS,OTHER WORM SPECIES,ALL OTHER CRABS,SOLDIER CRABS,CUNJEVOI,TROPICAL ROCKLOBSTER,EASTERN AND SOUTHERN ROCKLOBSTER,OCTOPUS,OYSTERS,PRAWNS,SALTWATER NIPPERS,SCALLOPS,SEA URCHINS,SQUID AND CUTTLEFISH,TURBAN SNAILS AND OTHER MOLLUSCS,OTHER SPINY CRAYFISH,FRESHWATER CATFISH EELTAILED,MURRAY COD,SILVER PERCH,OTHER NATIVE FIN FISH SPECIES,NONE,EASTERN FRESHWATER COD,TROUT COD,COCKLES MUSSELS AND PIPIS,SPANISH AND SPOTTED MACKEREL]","value":"AUSTRALIAN BASS AND ESTUARY PERCH"},{"key":"Group title","type":"text","value":"Combined bag limit and closed season"},{"key":"Group description","type":"textarea","value":"Australian Bass and Estuary Perch have a combined bag limit of 2 in total, with a possession limit of 4 in total. Commonly caught at night on baited hooks, particularly pieces of fish and earthworms.","key":"Characteristics"},{"type":"textarea","value":"Closely related and very similar to the shortfin eel, however, the dorsal fin starts much closer to the head on the long-finned eel.
